98W.title: Directed Group Study
98W.description: Directed group study consisting of supplementary problem sets, review sessions, and discussions related to chemical engineering.  Topics vary with instructor.

300.title: Professional Preparation: Supervised Teaching of Chemical Engineering
300.description: Discussion, problem review and development, guidance of large scale laboratory experiments, course development, supervised practice teaching.

160.title: Chemical Process Design
160.description: Design principles of chemical process equipment. Design of integrated chemical processes with emphasis upon economic considerations.

150B.title: Transport and Separation Processes
150B.description: Principles of mass transfer with application to chemical processes. Diffusion and convection. Simultaneous heat and mass transfer; mass transfer coefficients. Design of staged and continuous separations processes.

H193.title: Senior Honors Thesis
H193.description: A senior honors thesis is written in consultation with the student's faculty research advisor.  This is a required course for students wishing to graduate with honors in Chemical Engineering.

176.title: Principles of Electrochemical Processes
176.description: Principles and application of electrochemical equilibria, kinetics, and transport processes. Technical electrolysis and electrochemical energy conversion.

185.title: Technical Communication for Chemical Engineers
185.description: Development of technical writing and oral presentation skills in formats commonly used by chemical engineers.

162.title: Dynamics and Control of Chemical Processes
162.description: Analysis of the dynamic behavior of chemical processes and methods and theory of their control. Implementation of computer control systems on process simulations.

296.title: Special Study for Graduate Students in Chemical Engineering

154.title: Chemical Engineering Laboratory
154.description: Experiments in physical measurements, fluid mechanics, heat and mass transfer, kinetics, and separation processes. Emphasis on investigation of basic relationships important in engineering. Experimental design, analysis of results, and preparation of engineering reports are stressed.

250.title: Transport Processes
250.description: Basic differential relations of mass, momentum, and energy including creeping, laminar, and turbulent flow, boundary layers, convective-diffusion in heat and mass transfer, and simultaneous multicomponent mass and energy transport. Analytic mathematical solution of the equations of change using classical techniques including: separation of variables, similarity solutions, and Laplace and Fourier transforms.

140.title: Introduction to Chemical Process Analysis
140.description: Material and energy balances applied to chemical process systems. Determination of thermodynamic properties needed for such calculations. Sources of data. Calculation procedures.

256.title: Advanced Transport Phenomena
256.description: Formulation and rigorous analysis of the laws governing the transport of momentum, heat, and mass, with special emphasis on chemical engineering applications. Detailed investigation of laminar flows complemented by treatments of turbulent flow systems and hydrodynamic stability.

298.title: Seminar in Chemical Engineering
298.description: Lectures, reports, and discussions on current research in chemical engineering. Sections are operated independently and directed toward different topics.

180.title: Chemical Engineering Economics
180.description: Optimal design of chemical processes and unit operations, emphasizing the interactions between technical and economic considerations. Analysis of process risks. Chemical and biomolecular process design in the presence of uncertainties. Interest rate determinants and their effects on chemical process feasibility and choices. Relationships between structure and behavior of firms in the chemical processing industries. Multivariable input-output analyses.

196.title: Special Laboratory Study
196.description: Special laboratory or computational work under direction of one of the members of the staff.

170A.title: Biochemical Engineering
170A.description: This course intends to introduce chemical engineers to the basic concepts of biochemical engineering. The course focuses on the use of chemical engineering skills and principles in the analysis and design of biologically-based processes. The main emphasis will be on biochemical kinetics, heat and mass transfer, thermodynamics, and transport phenomena as they apply to enzyme catalysis, microbial growth and metabolism, fermentation and bioreactor design, product recovery and downstream processing. Fundamental topics in biological sciences will be introduced as necessary throughout the course.

240.title: Thermodynamics for Chemical Product and Process Design
240.description: Topics covered include molecular thermodynamics of pure substances and mixtures, interfacial thermodynamics, statistical mechanics, and computer simulations.

197.title: Field Study in Chemical Engineering
197.description: Supervised experience in off-campus organizations relevant to specific aspects and applications of chemical engineering. Written report required at the end of the term. Course does not satisfy unit or residence requirements for the bachelor's degree.

H194.title: Research for Advanced Undergraduates
H194.description: Original research under direction of one of the members of the staff.

244.title: Kinetics and Reaction Engineering
244.description: Molecular processes in chemical systems, kinetics and catalysis. Interaction of mass and heat transfer in chemical processes. Performance of systems with chemical reactors.

179.title: Process Technology of Solid-State Materials Devices
179.description: Chemical processing and properties of solid-state materials. Crystal growth and purification. Thin film technology. Application of chemical processing to the manufacture of semiconductors and solid-state devices.

142.title: Chemical Kinetics and Reaction Engineering
142.description: Analysis and prediction of rates of chemical conversion in flow and nonflow processes involving homogeneous and heterogeneous systems.

298C.title: Colloquium in Chemical Engineering
298C.description: Lectures, reports, and discussions on current research in chemical engineering.

143.title: Computational Methods in Chemical Engineering
143.description: The purpose of Chemical Engineering Modeling and Computations in Chemical Engineering is to teach students the methodologies used in setting up mathematical models of simple chemical processes and operations, and the numerical techniques used to simulate them.  Included are techniques to obtain physical properties of mixtures/solutions using equations of state.  This is followed by simple processes such as vapor liquid equilibrium, separation operations such as distillation, heat transfer, and chemical reactions in ideal reactors such as stirred tank and plug flow.  Later on, real chemical process equipment and processes are modeled and simulated, using many of the techniques learned earlier.  Programming languages such as Matlab and...

C178.title: Polymer Science and Technology
C178.description: An interdisciplinary course on the synthesis, characterization, and properties of polymer materials. Emphasis on the molecular origin of properties of polymeric materials and technological applications. Topics include single molecule properties, polymer mixtures and solutions, melts, glasses, elastomers, and crystals. Experiments in polymer synthesis, characterization, and physical properties.

40.title: Introduction to Chemical Engineering Design
40.description: Design and analysis of processes involving chemical change. Strategies for design, such as creative thinking and (re)definition of the design goal. Methods for analyzing designs, such as mathematical modeling, empirical analysis by graphics, and dynamic scaling by dimensional analysis. Design choices in light of process efficiency, product quality, economics, safety, and environmental issues.

195.title: Special Topics
195.description: Lectures and/or tutorial instruction on special topics.

198.title: Directed Group Study for Undergraduates
198.description: Supervised research on a specific topic. Enrollment is restricted; see Introduction to Courses and Curricula section in the General Catalog.

295P.title: Special Topics in Chemical Engineering: Introduction to New Product Development
295P.description: This course is part of the product development initative sponsored by the department of chemical engineering. It focuses on real-life practices and challenges of translating scientific discovery into commercial products. Its scope is limited in most circumstances to situations where some knowledge of chemical engineering, chemistry, and related disciplines might prove to be particularly useful. The course primarily uses case studies of real-world new product development situations to simulate the managerial and technical challenges that will confront students in the field. We will cover a wide range of topics including basic financial, strategic and intellectual property concepts for products, managing risk and uncertainity, the effective new product development team, the evolving role of corporate R&D, the new venture product company and the ethics of post-launch product management.

98.title: Directed Group Studies for Lower Division Undergraduates
98.description: Supervised research on a specific topic.
